<br>
Many of the same reasons posted above - lack of perspective, incorrect assumptions, and just plain bad data.  <br>
<br>
If and when you do collect some valid stuff, however, you need to do a couple things in your letters.<br>
<br>
First, quantify the points you think need attention.  Just saying &quot;We need better pets because we're always medding&quot; is subjective - meaning that behaviour will change from person to person - and vague - why are you always medding?  At what rate to you meditate?  What mob exactly are you fighting and how are you fighting it?  Further, just soloing a mob isn't the only part of the equation - and it is very likely to be among the lowest parts on VI's list.  You must be absolutely clear of what situation you are describing, why you think it needs to change, and suggest several possible corrections and why you think they would be corrections.  Your intent must be crystal clear.<br>
<br>
Second, spell check and grammar check your letter.  I'm not flaming you here - if you are going to send a letter to someone for serious consideration, you need to sound and look serious.  If you come across with low-quality writing, you will very likely have your letter discarded.  This game pulls millions for Sony and VI every year - they are NOT about to make changes based on what might be perceived as not-clearly-proposed changes.  Using things like &quot;a letter from us magicain's&quot; comes across as if the author was in Jr. High, and there is no way it's going to get the attention you want that way.<br>
<br>
Third - and this is somewhat linked with my first point - play the class all the way through.  People can level up to 16th in only a few hours of play.  There are folks who have put in *months* of play on several classes (and when I say months, I mean when they type /played, it comes back as 100-200 days of contiguous play).  You absolutely MUST have a solid grounding of knowledge in the thing before you can suggest that something is broken, much less suggest a fix for it.<br>
<br>
Sorry, man, I hope you understand I'm not dogging you.  I think you just might be finding that the class isn't right for you, or perhaps you just aren't dealing with the trials of it very well.  Keep plugging - life as a magician does pay off eventually.<br>
<br>
Luck - <br>
